General-purpose large language models lack real-time spatial perception, making it difficult to directly understand the user's current location, speed, direction, and the environment ahead, often resulting in context-irrelevant responses.  

Dynamic Route Echoing  
By employing multiplexing and sentence segmentation to recognize keywords such as "take me to" and "navigate to," the system avoids entering the general-purpose chat chain and instead directly transitions into the navigation state machine. This significantly reduces the response time for the first word, converting long-form model text into short, broadcastable instructions in real-time.  

Before the voice input reaches the large model, the system injects real-time information including the user's GPS coordinates, movement speed, direction, and visual recognition results of the environment ahead. This upgrades the AI from a "general-purpose chat assistant" to a "spatial perception assistant tailored for wayfinding scenarios."
